SIMPLE: decoct
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Decoct
<hw>De*coct"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Decocted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Decocting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>decoctus</ets>, p. p.
of <ets>decoquere</ets> to boil down; <ets>de-</ets> +
<ets>coquere</ets> to cook, boil. See <er>Cook</er> to decoct.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To prepare by boiling; to digest in hot or boiling
water; to extract the strength or flavor of by boiling; to make an
infusion of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To prepare by the heat of the stomach for
assimilation; to digest; to concoct.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To warm, strengthen, or invigorate, as if by
boiling.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Decoct</xex> their cold
blood.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Decoctible</ent>⟦br⟧
